    <section id="id7416888">
      <title>Memorandum</title>
      <para id="id7416894">a. sweet</para>
      <para id="id7416899">b. salty</para>
      <para id="id7416903">c. bitter</para>
      <para id="id7416907">d. sour</para>
      <para id="id7416911">When the nostrils are pinched together, scents cannot enter the nose, so you will only distinguish sweet, sour, salty and bitter.</para>
      <para id="id7416917">In the case of a cold: the same as above.</para>
      <para id="id7416922">The sense of smell in the animal world.</para>
      <para id="id7416926">Skunk: Protects itself by spraying a strong smelling / pungent secretion in the direction of the enemy.</para>
      <para id="id7416934">Jackal: Depends on its sense of smell when hunting. It also has scent glands that secrete scent as it goes along and helps it to find the way on its return.</para>
      <para id="id7416943">Dog:  Smells very well. Because of their well-developed sense of smell, dogs are used to sniff out drugs, explosives and even people in crowds. They also use their sense of smell when they are hunting.</para>
      <para id="id7416956">Antelope:  Uses its sense of smell to stay out of danger. If they smell an enemy, antelopes run off very quickly.</para>
      <para id="id7416967">Rhinoceros:  They also have scent glands underneath their feet to leave messages for other rhinoceroses.</para>
      <para id="id7416975">Hoopoe: Birds usually keep their nests very clean, but not the hoopoe. Part of its defence mechanism is to not clean the nest so that the smell will keep predators away.</para>
    </section>
